Commentary.Commentary: Right! West Indies have a task in their hand now. They will look to bat out the day without any damage. New Zealand, on the other hand, would be aiming to get a couple of wickets before Stumps on Day 2. Will they be able to do so and end the day on a high or will West Indies go unscathed? West Indies' innings coming your way shortly.

West Indies bowlers tried hard with the ball. They threw everything that they had to Williamson but that man just was not ready to get out. Kemar Roach and Shannon Gabriel were the picks of the bowlers for the West Indies as they got 3 apiece. Skipper Holder didn't get any wicket but bowled really tightly in his 31-overs spell, giving away just 60. Jospeh got the massive wicket of Williamson but that came pretty late. Chase too failed to get any wicket and he was smashed for a few as he gave away over 100 in his 25-over spell.

Earlier in the day, Williamson lost his overnight partner Taylor early but he knew what he had to do. He had to bat long and boy he did that and did it how. The marathon knock continued as he added 50-plus stands with Blundell, Mitchell and Jamieson. He brought up his 200 and then his 250 before falling, trying to accelerate. Jamieson got his maiden half ton and that's when the declaration came.

There comes the declaration! Yes! New Zealand have declared! What a massive score on the board for the Kiwis. What an innings from Kane Williamson! The Windies will be tired already after bowling over 145 overs. They have toiled hard but when Kane is in that kind of a form, you just can't do much.

West Indies have not had any luck go their way and they have only themselves to blame for it. The tourists struck early but could not capitalise. Roach even got the better of Kane Williamson but only to overstep. Roach and Gabriel got one wicket apiece in this session as well. The visitors need other bowlers to step up and show some fight with the ball for the remaining time they bowl in this innings. Can West Indies do some damage control or will New Zealand get some more runs quickly? Join us for the final session of Day 2 to find out.

Williamson stitched a tidy stand with Mitchell before the tourists saw his back. Williamson though after getting to his 3rd double ton has changed gears and Jamieson too has played with white ball intent. The pair has added 50 plus stand and it looks like they will add a few more before declaring.

Kane Williamson continues leading out the players. The New Zealand skipper's supreme, marathon knock continues as he heads into Tea just 6 runs shy of his best score in Tests. West Indies' nightmare continues as they are well and truly chasing this game.

So New Zealand continue to dominate and will look to dictate terms. West Indies, on the other hand, will have a lot of work to do and will look to find some inspiration in the second session. What is in store in the Afternoon Session? Join us for that to find out.

A better performance with the ball from West Indies but still not as good as they would have wanted. They started it well and have bowled fuller than Day 1. That has reaped them rewards as they have managed to get 2 wickets in the morning session. The tourists though started to lose way and would look to regroup and reenergize at the break. Kemar Roach and Shannon Gabriel were once again the bowlers to get the wickets.

New Zealand did not start the session well as they lost Ross Taylor early. Nicholls then joined his skipper. Williamson was once again brilliant and continued to dominate the West Indies bowlers. Getting to his 22nd Test ton. Nicholls too departed soon though. Kane continued his good work and has built a solid 65-run stand out of which Blundell has scored just 8.

Outstanding Williamson once again leads as the players head out for lunch. 103 runs and 2 wickets off the first session. A much improved performance from the tourists but still it is a session that will please New Zealand more than West Indies.

FOUR! HUNDRED FOR KANE WILLIAMSON! Tremendous innings from the New Zealand skipper. A classy knock from a classy player! Century number 22 in this format for the Kiwi captain. Phenomenal man with yet another masterclass in batting. The New Zealand skipper gets to his milestone in style! Length ball wide outside off, Williamson punches it through cover-point and gets to his ton. His teammates all get on their feet and applaud their talismanic skipper. Williamson removes his helmet and raises his bat and soaks in all the applause from his teammates and all the people on the ground.

OUT! Caught! No question about it being a bump ball and West Indies have their first wicket of the day. The first ball Gabriel has got right today and that has fetched him another wicket. Very good ball from Gabriel. He goes full around off. Taylor gets on his front foot to defend but the ball shapes away a tad and with good pace. It kisses the outside edge of Taylor's bat and goes straight into the mitts of the keeper. Shamarh Brooks, who is standing behind the stumps, takes a simple catch. The umpires check to see if it was a bump ball. Replays show it is clean as a whistle.
The umpires have a chat and has that ball bumped on its way to the keeper? The Soft Signal is OUT! Let's say what the replays have to say.

FOUR! First boundary of the day! Poor ball, asking to be punished and punished it was. Full on the pads, Taylor is a strong player on the leg side. He flicks it through square leg and gets a boundary.

Full and targetting the off pole. Good ball this from Roach. Taylor defends it to mid off to see off his first ball of the day.
First run of the day! On the pads, Williamson flicks it to deep backward square leg and gets a single. Moves to 98 with that.
Roach starts with a full ball around off. Williamson gets on his front foot and defends it to negotiate the first ball of the day.

We are all set for the action to begin on Day 2! The West Indies players are in a huddle with skipper, Jason Holder having a final word with his players before they take their respective positions in the field. Overnight batsmen, Kane Williamson and Ross Taylor walk out to resume their innings. The New Zealand skipper will face the first ball. Kemar Roach is all set to bowl the first over of the day.

It was a forgetful Day 1 for the West Indies and they will hope to have a much better outing. They were poor with their line and length and will look to be better with it. This has the potential to be a long day for the tourists and they will have to come out with intent. Can Holder and co. stage a fight back or will New Zealand build on their dominant start?

Hello and welcome to Day 2 of the first Test between New Zealand and West Indies. The hosts are in a very dominant position led by their skipper. Williamson is just 3 away from another Test ton and the Kiwi skipper will be eager to make a big one. He is joined by the extremely experienced Ross Taylor. The two will look to build on their 75-run stand.
... Day 2, Morning Session ...

The Windies bowling was quite wayward to begin with! They did not make most of the new ball. Also, they did not have a lot of luck on their side. There were times in the day where they did decently but without any success. They will now need to come out on Day 2 and take wickets quickly or they will fall well behind the 8-ball game. Do join us for that. Till then, goodbye and take care!

He won the toss and elected to bowl on a green surface with the idea of picking early wickets. He did get one but that's it. It was all New Zealand after that. Tom Latham and Kane Williamson added a 150-plus run stand. Latham departed 14 short of his ton but Williamson and Taylor continued the good work. The former is nearing his ton and the Kiwis would hope he continues and along with the rest, they can post a huge first innings score.
New Zealand's day quite easily! They will be mighty pleased with where they stand in the game. Holder, on the other hand, will be very disappointed with how things went along.

We are all set to begin the final session of Day 1. The West Indies players are out in the middle. Tom Latham and Kane Williamson will resume their innings for New Zealand. Jason Holder will start the proceedings for the final session of Day 1.
Day 1, Session 3 ...

How will West Indies come out for the final session? They looked down and jaded at the end of the session and will need to find a way to respond. Williamson and Latham will look to continue more of the same and dominate the first day of this Test. What is in store for us in the final session of the day? Join us at 1610 local (0310 GMT) for the final session of the day.

Not the session West Indies would have hoped for after winning the toss. One cannot blame, Holder for opting to bat on a pitch that is showered with grass. The ball though did not do as much as expected. The tourists have also failed to hit the right areas as they have not bowled the right areas. Gabriel got an early success but that was it.

After being put into bat on a lush green pitch, New Zealand lost debutant Will Young early. Skipper, Kane Williamson and his deputy, Tom Latham though have been solid and have showed great patience. The pair have added a calm 85 and are looking on course for a big stand.

A solid session of play for the Kiwis. They have taken their time and laid a solid platform at the start of this Test. West Indies haven't been able to trouble New Zealand in the first session of this game and they will have to revisit their plan.

No waiting from Young as he knows he is dead in front. Young's debut does not last long and West Indies have an early breakthrough.

Done and dusted with the national anthems and now we are all set for the action to begin. The West Indies players are in a huddle with their skipper, Jason Holder giving final words of motivation before his troops take the field. Tom Latham walks out along with debutant, Will Young to open the innings for the hosts. Kemar Roach is set to start the proceedings with the new ball. A very emotional moment for the West Indies pacer as he lost his father recently. The West Indies players are wearing a black arm band for Kemar's late father. The players take a knee for a stand against racism. The umpire says play and here we go!
Both sets of players make their way out for their respective national anthems. We are not far away from the start.
New Zealand (Playing XI) - Tom Latham, Will Young, Kane Williamson (C), Ross Taylor, Henry Nicholls, Tom Blundell (WK), Daryl Mitchell, Kyle Jamieson, Tim Southee, Neil Wagner, Trent Boult.

West Indies (Playing XI) - Kraigg Brathwaite, John Campbell, Shamarh Brooks, Darren Bravo, Roston Chase, Jermaine Blackwood, Shane Dowrich (WK), Jason Holder (C), Kemar Roach, Shannon Gabriel, Alzarri Joseph.

New Zealand skipper, Kane Williamson, admits they would have bowled first had they won the toss. Tells they will look to stick to their plans. Says that the guys are excited as it has been a long time. Informs Watling and Conway miss out. Tells the context of WTC brings different dynamics. Tells every game is a tough one and it is all about addressing what is in front of them.

West Indies skipper, Jason Holder, says that looking at the wicket there is a lot of grass. Tells the bounce was inconsistent in the warm up games and hence the decision. Tells the guys spent some time in the middle in the warm ups and he is happy. Holder says there is always something for the bowlers on the first day. Holder informs Cornwall, Hetmyer, Keemo Paul and Chemar Holder are the ones missing out.

TOSS - After a long delay we are finally all set for the spin of coin. New Zealand skipper, Kane Williamson and West Indies captain, Jason Holder are out in the middle. Up goes the coin. Holder calls Heads and it comes down as Heads. WEST INDIES OPT TO BOWL!

PITCH REPORT - Ian Bishop is down for the pitch report. Ian Bishop says that the overhead condition means it is not too warm. Tells there is a cool breeze. Bishop says there is 15m grass on it. Bishop says that looking at the wicket one feels to continue the trend of winning the toss and bowling.

Update 1200 local (2300 GMT, 2nd December) - The umpires have shifted the toss to 1232 local after further inspection and the first ball is scheduled to be bowled at 1300 local. Let us hope there are no further delays. It will be a 2 hour 50 minute session with Tea scheduled at 1550 local.

Update 1140 local (2240 GMT, 2nd December) - More good news! The rain has gone, the weather has warmed up a bit, the covers are completely gone and the players are out warming up. The toss is scheduled at 1210 local while the play is scheduled to start by 1240 local.

Update 1115 local (2215 GMT, 2nd Decemeber) - We have some great news. The umbrellas are off, the rain has stopped and the covers are coming off. Hopefully the rain now stays away and we get started very soon.

Roston Chase is caught for a quick chat. Chase says they are looking forward to the tour and are eager to put on a better show than the last time. On being asked what he feels is different, Chase says that they were a lot inexperienced the last time they visited this country. Feels the guys are now more experienced and have played in different venues. Tells they were disappointed not to win the series in England. Chase says that he asked the groundsman if he was shaving off any but tells he was told they were just going to roll. Chase smiles and belives that he was just joking. Adds that the pitch here holds true.

UPDATE 1036 local (2136 GMT, 2nd December) - Not the start any cricket fan likes to see. We are welcomed with an uninvited guest in the form of rain. Which inevitably means the toss is delayed. The groundsman  believes the weather to clear by 1300 local. Let's hope it clears out before that and we have action sooner rather than later.

West Indies, on the other hand, will be desperate to avenge for the T20I series loss and make a statement with a strong showing in the longest format. Jason Holder and his troops have shown promise in red ball cricket and will be eager to continue their progress. Both sides are completely different from the T20Is. An exciting contest awaits us. Can the team from Caribbean spring a surprise or will the Black Caps show their superiority? Stay tuned for the toss.

Hello and welcome to the Day 1 of the first Test between New Zealand and West Indies. The hosts return to Test cricket for the first time after almost 9 months and the last time the hosts played a Test series at home, they whitewashed India. The Kiwis will be looking to do more of the same to the side from the Caribbean. They completely outplayed them in the shortest format and will look to do the same in the longest format too.
UPDATE 1505 local (0205 GMT) - Yes! We have the news. Play to begin at 1520 local. Just around 15 minutes from now.

UPDATE 1500 local (0200 GMT) - The rain seems to have stopped. The covers are being removed. Blue skies out of nowhere at the moment. The umpires are strolling out in the middle, inspecting the conditons. It shouldn't take long for the resumption of West Indies' second innings.

Right! West Indies still trail by 381 runs. They will be batting again as Williamson has enforced the follow on. There's plenty of overs left in the day and the Kiwis will look to repeat what they have done so far in the day. Also, just to update, as soon as the Windies innings ended, it started to drizzle heavily and the covers were quickly brought on to protect the 22-yard strip. We will keep you posted.

Windies batters just had no answers to the Southee masterclass who got good support from the others to wrap this innings up quickly. After getting no success in 26 overs last evening, the Kiwi bowlers decided to do the magic on Day 3. Southee struck in his first over and gave the team a perfect start. It was all about their swing bowlers after that. They got some sort of resistance only from Blackwood and Holder. Southee eventually ended up with a 4-fer while Wagner and Jamieson got two. Boult got just one to his name.

The West Indies openers were able to weather the storm last evening and they probably needed to do something similar in the first hour but they failed to do so. The others who followed couldn't do much either and they were soon left reeling with the side gone with the score not crossing 100. Skipper Holder and Blackwood then added 40 runs between them to offer some resistance. However, Blackwood fell in the 4th over of the second session. Holder stayed till the end but lost partners from the other end.

UPDATE 1344 local (0044 GMT) - Good news! The covers are coming off. We are not too far away from the resumption. It will start at 1350 local.

UPDATE 1337 local (0037 GMT) - We were just minutes away from the 2nd session on Day 3 but it has started to drizzle. The groundsmen quickly brings the covers on to protect the pitch. Let's hope this goes away quickly.

It was Southee who took the ball first up and struck in the first over itself as he removed Campbell. Brooks became his 2nd victim in the next over and Boult said I should join the party too. He got rid of Brathwaite and West Indies were in all sorts of trouble. Bravo and Chase then weathered the storm for a while but eventually fell to Jamieson and Wagner respectively. Holder, the Windies skipper, was dismissed for nothing but Wagner overstepped and gave him life. He along with Blackwood have now added 35 runs but the task for them is much bigger. Will they be able to continue the fight when we return for the second session of this moving day? We will soon find out. Join us in a bit.

We are all set to begin Day 3. The New Zealand players are out in the middle. Kraigg Brathwaite and John Campbell will resume their innings for West Indies. Tim Southee will start the proceedings for Day 3.

Hello and welcome to Day 3! The Kiwis put on a massive score the other day, courtesy, a brilliant double ton from skipper Kane Williamson. It is now up to the bowlers to do the job. They bowled 26 overs on Day 2 but Brathwaite and Campbell did well to negotiate that phase. A new day will bring new challenges for both sides. Will the Kiwis be able to strike or will the Windies openers be able to continue their stand from the last evening? We will know all these in a short while when the action resumes.
... Day 3, Session 1 ...

Right! 49-run unbeaten opening stand! On Day 3, when these two will come out to bat, the target for them will be to bat as long as they could. West Indies bat long and would hope that all their batters do well and take the game deep. The hosts, on the other hand, would return on Day 3 and look to get rid of this stand first and then go about their business. Day 2 belongs to the Kiwis but the way these two are batting, the New Zealand bowlers might have to do the toil if they are to take the honors for the 3rd day as well. So, when we return for Day 3, it is going to be another intriguing day's play! Do join us for the same. Until then, it is goodbye from our side. Take care!

Then came the Windies openers! They were tested by Southee and Boult in the first few overs but they weathered the storm. Jamieson too bowled well but couldn't produce the magic delivery. Wagner arrived and started bowling the bouncers but Campbell and Brathwaite did well to negotiate him as well.

Nothing much to talk about the Windies bowling. They weren't bad but just couldn't find the way to get the big wicket of Williamson. Gabriel struck early, Roach removed Nicholls but after that, it was hard work for the bowlers. Roach had managed to get the wicket of Williamson but he overstepped and gave Kane another chance. It was Joseph who eventually got the wicket of Williamson but not before the Kiwi skipper got to his first-ever 250 in Tests. Declaration eventually came and that would've given a sigh of relief to the Windies bowlers who had to toil really hard in the course of these 2 days, bowling 145 overs.

It was all about Kane Williamson! The day started with New Zealand losing Ross Taylor early. Nicholls didn't last long too but Kane continued as he got good support from the likes of Blundell, Mitchell, and Jamieson. He went past 250 and got out trying to up the ante. Jamieson got to his maiden half ton and the Kiwis declared after that.
Fine phase of play for West Indies! Their openers have managed to remain unscathed! But the day will belong to the Kiwis and especially to their skipper Kane Williamson for his classy knock of 251.

Jason Holder, West Indies skipper, says that he is disappointed with his team's batting. Adds that they will look to improve on their batting. Mentions they would look to improve their bowling and would look to work on the areas they need to bowl on. Holder also says that they need to start delivering and understand that they need to fight harder and find a way to bat well. Credits Blackwood and Joseph for batting well and putting up a fight. Informs Dowrich is doubtful for the next Test as he is still complaining about pain. Ends by saying the support staff has been excellent and now they need to come back strong in the next Test.

Kane Williamson, New Zealand skipper, is named the Player of the Match. He starts off by saying that it has been a brilliant victory for them. Adds that his knock was special and crucial for the team. Mentions it was great to spend time in the middle and build some partnerships. Credits Tom Latham for his excellent batting. Williamson says it was a collective effort from their batsmen to post a huge score in the first innings. Adds it was important for their bowlers to be patient and continue to hit the right lengths. Ends by saying it was a really good win but they need to focus on the second Test now.

Blackwood got to his ton. Joseph was eyeing one too. They frustrated the Kiwis. This stand is probably the only positive the Windies could take from this game. However, it was just a matter of one wicket and once the Kiwis got Joseph, they got the other two quickly. A comprehensive win for the hosts.

They were bundled out for 138. The Kiwis enforced the follow-on and it seemed they would get all the 20 wickets on Day 3 itself but then came a fight back. Joseph and Blackwood amassed a 100-plus run stand. They took the game to Day 4.
Windies did start off their innings well as their openers put up a 50-run stand but it all went wrong for them on Day 3. 15 wickets is what they lost.
It was all New Zealand in this game. First they put up a massive first innings total courtesy a double ton by their skipper.

So just over an hour is what it took for the Kiwis to take the remaining three wickets however, it was not before Blackwood scored his ton. Joseph also continued to show fight on Day 4 but once he fell, the other two wickets fell in no time.

The hosts, on the other hand, are just the three wickets away and if we see Dowrich batting then 4 wickets away from claiming a 1-0 lead. They would be hoping to take the wickets quickly and finish the game. Will that be the case or the Windies still have some fight left in them? We will find out...
The pair really fought back and have frustrated the Kiwis. Can they continue that though? Can they help the Windies avoid an innings defeat? They are still 185 runs away from that.

Hello and welcome to the coverage of what could well be the last day or maybe even the last session of this Test. We saw 15 wickets falling on Day 3 and had it not been for the Joseph-Blackwood stand, the game would have probably ended yesterday itself.
... Day 4, Session 1 ...

Right! New Zealand well and truly on top, in spite of that superb unbeaten 107-run stand between Blackwood and Joseph. They are still ahead by 185 runs and need just 3 wickets to win the game. They will get good rest and would look to come back and knock the remaining wickets to take the lead in this 2-game series. The visitors, on the other hand, would want these to bat and bat and bat. It will not be easy for them in the first hour of Day 4. Will the Kiwis be able to get those wickets quickly or will Blackwood and Joseph be able to tire them more? We will find out all the answers on Day 4. Join us for the same. For now, it is goodbye from our side. Cheers and take care!

Williamson enforced the follow on and West Indies were off to a worst possible start as Boult struck in the 2nd over of the innings. Things got bad to worse for them as Wagner got two in the same over. The score soon read 5/53 before Holder and Blackwood resisted again, but for just a short while. Holder got out playing a rash stroke and it looked like we will have the result on Day 3 itself, in spite of a few rain interruptions. And then Blackwood met Joseph and that was the start of a terrific stand that troubled the Kiwis but they just failed to go past the association of Blackwood and Joseph. They threw everything they had at both of them but it just didn't go their way at all. And it was a tough final session for the Kiwi bowlers.

The day would still belong to the Kiwis as they have taken 15 wickets in this game. 9 in the first innings and 6 here. It was Southee show in the morning as New Zealand rolled over West Indies in the first innings. He got good support from the other bowlers as well. Apart from skipper Holder and Blackwood, none of the Windies batters could offer any sort of resistance. It was a sorry batting display from them.

Terrific counter-attack from Blackwood and Joseph and they have taken the game into Day 4. At one point, it looked like the Kiwis will be able to wrap up the things well before Stumps but these two had different ideas. They just went from strength to strength and kept on piling the runs. A few missed chances didn't help New Zealand's cause.

FOUR! SLAMMED AWAY! This is good batting from Joseph here. He is enjoying the batting it seems. Full and wide outside off, he takes a long stride forward and drills the drive through backward point. It races away to the fence. Shake of the head from Southee.
Short on middle, tucked away on the leg side for one.
Full and outside off, Joseph looks to drive but it takes the inner half and goes to deep mid-wicket. Before the fielder from the ring can get to the ball, three more for Joseph.
Full and on the pads, clipped to fine leg for an easy single.

DRINKS! These two are going hard at the ball and are scoring a few runs but are living dangerously. New Zealand need just 3 wickets to seal the deal on Day 3 itself. Plenty of time left in the day for them to knock the remaining wickets, weather permitting. Let's see if these two continue to battle out.
Full and wide outside off, Joseph drives it towards mid off uppishly. It bounces short of Williamson. A single taken.
On off, pushed back to the bowler.
Full and wide outside off, Joseph looks to go big but ends up slicing it over gully. Two taken.
Length ball around off, pushed to the left of the bowler. The ball goes to the right of mid off and they sneak a single.
Outside off on a length. An easy leave for Blackwood.
Bouncer on middle, Blackwood ducks under it.
FOUR! DRILLED THROUGH THE COVERS! That is some shot from Joseph. A low full toss around off, he creams the drive through the covers. Classic cover drive. 13 from the over.
Shortish and on middle, worked towards mid-wicket.
Beaten! Short and just around off, shapes away as Joseph pokes at it.
FOUR! Clipped through square leg from Joseph. Full ball on the pads, Joseph uses his wrists and flicks it through square leg and bags himself a boundary.
On the pads again, it is worked towards fine leg for one.

FOUR! FIFTY FOR BLACKWOOD! He is the only positive for the Windies with the bat. He has done really well for these runs. Got himself in and then took the bowlers on. A short ball on the body, he clips it fine. The fine leg fielder runs to his right, dives and tries to pull the ball back in play but fails to do so. Blackwood raises his bat to his teammates.
Bangs it short and shows some aggression. Joseph ducks under it. Wagner keeps staring at him as he goes past the umpire.
A solid front foot defense from him this time.
Full and wide outside off, Joseph lifts it over cover-point and gets a brace.

EDGY! A length ball around off, Joseph looks to defend but gets an inside edge on the pad. The ball goes past the sticks and runs to the fence at fine leg. But Jamieson, the big man, runs to his left towards fine leg and makes a diving stop. Saves two for the side. Excellent commitment.
Short and wide outside off, Blackwood cuts it through cover-point. The third man fielder runs to his right and stops the ball but Blackwood gets three.
Back of a length and around off, punched towards the short cover fielder.
Neil Wagner is back on. 6-0-36-2 are his figures so far.
Play and a miss! Joseph is lured into the drive as he plays it away from his body. Beaten.
Fuller and on middle, Joseph flicks it well but Jamieson moves to his right swiftly to stop the ball.
Bouncer on middle, Alzarri ducks under it.
Around off on a length, Joseph is solid in defense.
Short ball on middle, Blackwood hops and works it to fine leg for one.
Bouncer down the leg side. Blackwood ducks.
Short delivery on off, Blackwood looks to cut but gets an outside edge. It goes towards first slip on one bounce. The fielder misfields and concedes a single.
Back of a length on off, Blackwood pushes it to mid off.
Around off on a length, pushed back to the bowler.
Good drive but for no run. Full and wide outside off, driven straight to mid off.
Sharp bouncer around off, Blackwood does well to get away from the firing line.
In the channel outside off, left alone.
Good length and outside off, left alone.
Very full and outside off, Joseph squeezes it out towards backward point.

In the air... safe! Chance for a run out. Missed. Who missed? Well, Kane Williamson. Probably for the first time he has done something and it has not gone his way. Fuller and outside off, Blackwood looks to hammer it over mid off but once again it goes off the toe end. It falls well short of Williamson. But West Indies want to get it done quickly it seems as they go for the risky single. Williamson collects the ball and has a shy at the non-striker's end but he misses. Blackwood made a big dive but had Williamson hit, he would've been short.
Bouncer and on middle, Blackwood sits under it.

In the air... safe! That went miles in the air but Jamieson failed to get there. A length ball outside off, Blackwood looks to hammer it over the bowler's head but miscues it high in the air. Jamieson from mid on runs back and tries to catch but he fails to get there. Two taken.
Good length and on middle and leg, Blackwood looks to work it on the leg side but gets an inside edge on the pad.
Trent Boult is back on.
Full and swinging in but it is wide outside off so Joseph lets it be. End of a successful over form Mitchell.
Length ball outside off, left alone by Alzarri.
Full and wide outside off, Joseph shoulders arms.
Alzarri Joseph is the new batsman in.

OUT! LBW! Yes, Mitchell has got his man. He has his maiden Test wicket. Poor, poor batting from him. He got a life just 1 ball ago. He played a reckless shot then and he tried something similar but this time he has to go. Fuller and around off and middle, Holder looks to slog it on the leg side via a flick but he misses it completely. He is struck on the pads. A massive appeal and the finger goes up. Holder asks for the review straightaway but that looked out to the naked eye. Let's see what the replays have got to show. No bat involved, Ultra Edge confirms. The Ball Tracker shows it to be clipping the leg pole. Holder has to go and Mitchell and the Kiwis celebrate.
Mitchell has surely got his wicket now. Or has he? Holder has been given out LBW but the Windies skipper takes it upstairs.
Length ball around middle, it is clipped through square leg for a couple.

NO BALL!  Holder is caught at covers. Holder is shocked! He is not sure what he has done here. A soft dismissal. Mitchell is delighted. Full ball outside off, Holder drills the drive but straight to the cover fielder. Mitchell Santner, the substitute makes no mistake. But hang on. Mitchell has overstepped. And he will have to wait for his maiden Test wicket.
Fuller and around off, defended towards mid off.
FOUR! Up and over! Blackwood is playing a little gem of an innings here. Short and wide outside off, he slashes it over backward point and it races away to the fence. He moves to 40 in just 48 balls.
Goes slightly full. Blackwood works it towards mid-wicket.
Short and on middle, pushed towards mid-wicket.
Good length and around off, this one rises awkwardly. Blackwood does well to defend it out.
Back of a length ball on middle and leg, Blackwood defends it out.

EDGED AND FOUR! Blackwood is going after the wide ones right now. Full and wide outside off, Jermaine throws his bat at it as he looks to drive but ends up getting a thick outside edge that goes well over the leaping slip cordon for a boundary.

EDGY! Length ball just outside off, Blackwood looks to defend but is squared up. The outside edge goes past the diving gully fielder. Before one of the fielder can do the mop up work, they take three.
Length ball around off, poked towards the on side.
Short this time, Blackwood forces it back to the bowler.
Length ball around middle, pushed towards mid on for nothing.
Full again, Blackwood drives it towards cover.
Fuller and around off, pushed towards the off side.
Daryl Mitchell is on now.

Another one goes down! This time it is Blundell who puts it down. A length ball angled in. Holder looks to defend but the ball comes back in sharply. It takes the inside edge and goes to the left of the keeper. Blundell moves to that side and gets his gloves to it but it doesn't stick. Two drops in two balls. The batsmen get two runs.
Dropped! Full and wide outside off, Holder goes for the drive but ends up hitting it uppishly towards point fielder. Young there dives to his left, gets both the hands but spills it in the end.
Goes to play this time as Jamieson pitches it fuller and around off, but this one moves away sharply to beat the outside edge.
This time he covers his sticks and offers no shot.
Beauty! Just outside off and on a good length, Holder pokes at it to get beaten. He played for the away swing but it went straight.
In the channel outside off, Holder shoulders arms.
FOUR! Short again and Blackwood hammers it. He is not going to bog down to this short stuff. He swivels and slams it over mid-wicket and it races away to the fence.
Back of a length and on middle, Blackwood hops and keeps it out.
Short ball on middle, it is pushed back to the bowler. Wagner quickly picks the ball and threatens to throw the ball at the stumps.
Short and just outside off, Blackwood sways away from the line.
FOUR! That is put away! Short ball on middle, Blackwood pulls it over the bowler's head for a boundary.
Back of a length on off, Blackwood pushes it to covers.
FOUR! Good shot! Length delivery on middle, Holder flicks it towards fine leg for a boundary.
Length ball outside off, Holder shoulders arms to this one.
Full and outside off, Holder offers no shot to this one.
Good length ball on off, Holder keeps it out.
Back of a length on off, Holder defends it off the back foot.

EDGED BUT DROPPED! Short and wide outside off, Blackwood throws the willow at it but gets a thick outside edge. The ball goes high over Taylor at first slip. He leaps high and gets hands to it but the rebound drops away from him. Good effort.
Short again, this time he nudges it down to fine leg for one.
SIX! BOOM! Enough of your short stuff says Blackwood and takes Wagner on. Short and around off and middle, Blackwood swivels and hammers it way over the deep square leg fence. That went way back.
Good stop! Shortish and around middle, Blackwood pushes it to the right of the bowler. Wagner dives that side and pushes it towards mid-wicket.
Bouncer but this one is down the leg side. Blackwood lets it be.
Short again, pushed towards mid on this time.
Back of a length and just outside off, pushed towards the cover fielder.
Jason Holder is the new batsman in.

OUT! LBW! Yes, there is no bat and it is hitting the wicket too. Chase has been removed with an absolute ripper of a delivery from Jamieson. It is the inswinging yorker from him and Chase is all over the place as he tries to keep it out. He misses to get hit on the pad. A loud appeal follows and the umpire agrees. Chase opts to challenge the onfield call. But it won't really help him because Ultra Edge shows no bat and the Ball Tracker shows it to be crashing on the middle pole. Chase has to go.
DRS TIME! Chase has been given out LBW but he calls for the DRS. That looked really, really close and if there is no bat involved, Chase is walking back.
Good length and around off, Chase is solid in defense again.
Length ball around off, Chase flicks it towards mid-wicket.
Shortish and around off, pushed towards the off side.
FIVE WIDES! Jamieson goes short but it goes well over the batsman and the leaping keeper. Wided and it races away to the fence too.
Length ball around off, kept out by Chase.
Fuller and around off, blocked.
Short and outside off, Jermaine ducks under it.

Short delivery on off, Blackwood looks to play an upper cut but misses it. It goes towards the keeper where Blundell appeals for caught behind and the umpire raises his finger. Blackwood reviews it! Ultra Edge shows there is a flat line when the ball passes the bat. The decision is overturned and Blackwood survives.
Bouncer from Wagner, Blackwood sits under it.
Bumper again from Wagner, Blackwood does well to duck under it.
Bouncer on middle, Blackwood ducks under it.
FOUR! Terrific shot! Full on off, Blackwood drives it through mid off for a boundary.
Outside off, Roston shoulders arms to this one.
BEATEN! Good length ball outside off, Chase looks to drive but misses it.
Good length delivery outside off, Chase offers no shot to this one.
Full on middle, Blackwood flicks it through mid-wicket for a single.
Good length ball on off, Blackwood pushes it to covers.
WIDE! Length delivery wide outside off, Blackwood lets it go.
Back of a length on off, Blackwood defends it off the back foot.
FOUR! Nice shot! Length ball on middle, Chase flicks it through square leg for a boundary.
Bouncer from Wagner, Chase does well to duck under it.
Back of a length on off, Chase looks to defend but gets an outside edge. It goes past second slip towards third man. The batsmen get two runs.
Length delivery on off, Blackwood punches it towards covers for a single.
FOUR! Good shot! Full on middle, Blackwood lofts it over mid on for a boundary.
NO BALL! Wagner oversteps! Length delivery on middle, Blackwood keeps it out.
Full and around off, pushed back to the bowler.
Neil Wagner to bowl from the other end.
This one keeps low. But Chase does well to bring his bat down in time to defend. A maiden to begin the final session on Day 3.
Lovely delivery! The last one came back in and this one goes other way after pitching. Chase looks to defend but misses.
Shortish and around off, this one comes back on. Chase does well to work it around the corner.
Misses the line and bowls the full ball down the leg side. Chase looks to flick but misses.
Outside off, left alone.
A good length ball outside off to begin, Chase shoulders arms.

Right! We are back for the final session. The rain has gone. The lights have improved too. Let's hope we don't have another interruption here. The Kiwi players walk out to the field first and Jermaine Blackwood and Roston Chase follow them out in the middle. Kyle Jamieson will start for New Zealand with the ball. Here we go...
... Day 3, Session 3 ...

UPDATE 1625 local (0325 GMT) - And the good news is that the rain has stopped and the covers are being removed. The umpires are out in the middle, having a word with the groundsman. Looks a lot brighter than what it was when the players went back.

Trent Boult struck with the ball first this time and then Wagner's double wicket over forced West Indies on the back foot again. And you just can't keep Southee out of the picture so he took one himself. They will hope that they get on the field quickly and roll through the remaining batters. Let's hope that the rain goes away quickly and we are back for the final session. Stay tuned.

So, as the drizzle continues, the umpires have called for an early Tea. Smart move. However, the moves from the Windies batters haven't been smart so far. Campbell got out playing an out of character shot while his opening partner did the same. Bravo and Brooks didn't last long either and West Indies are staring down the barrel at the moment. They are still 351 runs behind and have just 6 wickets remaining. They are reeling at 30/4 at the moment.
Outside off, Jermaine offers no shot to this one.
Back of a length on off, Blackwood taps it to point.
UPDATE 1610 local (0310 GMT) - Rain is in the air. And it has also got really dark out there. The umpires have called for the covers. And we have another rain interruption.
Full on off, Blackwood drives it through covers. The batsmen get two runs.
Short delivery outside off, Blackwood offers no shot to this one.
Length delivery outside off, Blackwood offers no shot to this one.
Full on middle, Blackwood flicks it to mid-wicket.
Length ball outside off, Chase offers no shot to this one.
Full on middle, Blackwood flicks it through square leg for a single.
Southee bowls a bumper, Blackwood ducks under it.
Full on middle, Blackwood drives it to mid on.
Full and wide outside off, driven well but straight to the cover fielder.
Jermaine Blackwood is the new batsman in.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Another one bites the dust and it is Southee who gets a wicket now. Poor, poor stuff from Brathwaite. Short and wide outside off, Brathwaite looks to upper cut but gets a faint edge to the keeper. Blundell makes no mistake. New Zealand are on fire here.
Roston Chase is the new batsman in.

OUT! CAUGHT! Another one goes. Wagner gets second wicket in the over. He is delighted. Brooks fails again. A length ball on the pads, Brooks goes for the flick again. This time he hits it uppishly and there is a fielder at square leg. Conway, the substitute, there makes no mistake.
Bouncer on middle, Brooks ducks under it.
Brooks is off the mark with a fine flick. Full ball on middle, he flicks it through square leg. The fine leg fielder comes around but by the time he returns the ball to the keeper, two taken.
Full and outside off, Brooks leaves it alone.
Shamarh Brooks is the new batsman in.

OUT! TAKEN! Wagner strikes on the second ball of his spell and it is the massive wicket of Bravo. A couple of good shots and he is dismissed. Wagner is fired up. Good length and outside off, Bravo pokes at it without moving his feet. The outside edge goes to the left of Southee at second slip. He tumbles to that side and takes a fine catch.
Length ball on middle, Brathwaite flicks it through square leg for a single.
Neil Wagner is into the attack now.
Good length delivery outside off, Bravo offers no shot to this one.
Bouncer on middle, Bravo ducks under it.
Back of a length outside off, Bravo offers no shot to this one.
FOUR! Have some of that now. Bravo, you beauty. Overpitched again and outside off as well. Bravo hammers it over extra cover for a boundary. Intent from Darren.
FOUR! SHOT! That is classy cover drive! One of the best shots in match. Full and wide outside off, Bravo leans into the shot and strokes it through the covers. Holds the pose for the cameras there!
Good length delivery on off, Bravo defends it off the back foot.
Good length ball outside off, Brathwaite offers no shot to this one.
Outside off, Kraigg shoulders arms to this one.
Good length delivery on off, Brathwaite defends it off the back foot.
FOUR! Wonderful shot! Full on middle, Brathwaite flicks it through mid-wicket for a boundary.
Back of a length outside off, Brathwaite offers no shot to this one.
Length ball outside off, Brathwaite leaves it alone.
Good length delivery on off, Bravo keeps it out.
Outside off, Darren offers no shot to this one.
Length delivery outside off, Bravo lets it go.
Back of a length on off, Bravo defends it off the back foot.
BEATEN! Full and outside off, Bravo looks to drive but misses it.
Good length delivery on off, Bravo keeps it out.
Full on off, Brathwaite pushes it through covers. The fielder chases it and does well to stop it. The batsmen get two runs.
Bouncer on middle, Brathwaite does well to duck under it.
Back of a length on middle, Brathwaite pushes it to mid on.
Outside off, Brathwaite offers no shot to this one.
BEATEN! Full and outside off, Brathwaite looks to drive but misses it.
Length delivery outside off, Brathwaite offers no shot to this one.
Full ball on off, Darren keeps it out.
Outside off, Bravo shoulders arms to this one.
FOUR! Whipped and whipped in style! Bravo is off the mark with a fine flick. Full and on middle, Bravo uses his wrists and whips it through square leg for a boundary.
Full on middle, Brathwaite flicks it through mid-wicket for a single.
Good length ball outside off, Kraigg shoulders arms to this one.
Back of a length down the leg side, Brathwaite leaves it alone.
WIDE! Southee bowls a bouncer, Brathwaite ducks under it.
Length delivery outside off, Bravo lets it go.
Good length delivery on off, Bravo keeps it out.
Back of a length on off, Bravo defends it off the back foot.
Darren Bravo is the new batsman in.

OUT! CAUGHT! Yes! There is no conclusive evidence for the third umpire to overturn the onfield call. Looked touch and go. An absolute ripper of a delivery from Boult. He pitches it just outside off, Campbell is squared up as he looks to defend with hard hands. The induced outside edge goes to the second slip fielder. Latham catches it really low and New Zealand celebrate. Campbell is not going anywhere. The two umpires get together and refer it upstairs. The soft signal is out. That is going to play a big role. Let's see what the replays show. It looks really inconclusive there. With one angle it looks like the fingers are under the ball while another one suggests that it might have kissed the turf. Tough decision to make and the third umpire goes with the onfield call. Campbell has to go. New Zealand have struck early in this innings.

Has that carried to the slip fielder? The soft signal is out. The third umpire needs to have conclusive evidence to overturn the onfield call. It looks really tough but with soft signal is out, the third umpire might go that way.
Campbell is off the mark! Boult goes full and outside off, Campbell looks to drive but a thick outside edge is induced. Luckily for him it goes through the gap between gully and point. Two taken.
Good length and outside off, Campbell lets it be.
Trent Boult to bowl from the other end.
Around off on a length, defended back to the bowler. Quality first over but equally well negotiated by Brathwaite.
Full again but this one is outside off, Brathwaite drives it towards the cover fielder.
Good length and around off, pushed towards mid on.
Brathwaite is up and running with a couple. Southee dishes it full and on the pads, Brathwaite flicks it wide of the fine leg fielder and gets two.
Goes full and around middle, Brathwaite flicks it towards mid-wicket.
Southee is right on the money! A length ball outside off, this one comes back in but Brathwaite covers his stumps and lets it go to the keeper. Good leave in the end.

And we are back for the action again! The two umpires stride out first and the Kiwi players follow them. Kraigg Brathwaite and John Campbell are the West Indies openers. Tim Southee is the man with the ball again. Here we go...
